We begin with the line given by the first equation, $y=\green{2}x-\pink{4}
$. We know the $y$-intercept is $(0,\pink{-4})$, so this is one of our points. Since the slope of the line is $\green{2}$, we know that another point on the line is $(1,\pink{-4}+\green{2})$, which is the point $(1,-2)$.

In a similar manner, we will find that the line given by the second equation passes through $(0,4)$ and $(-1,-2)$.
